videos.title: Is edge computing really faster?
videos.description: Edge computing is becoming a popular way to deliver modern web applications. Let‚Äôs find out if the Edge is really faster by comparing Firebase to Vercel Edge Functions with Next.js.

comments.commentTitle: I prefer tatooine-west-4 for all my deployments since the average distance to end users is about the same for everyone.
so basically edge = bring server closer to the consumer, while CDN = bring static files closer  to the consumer.
I love how ~800ms is unacceptably slow, but at my work I regularly do queries on a database that should take less than a second, but they somehow made take up to 20 seconds.

The time from router A to B does not depends always on the distance, it depends also on the route contracted between the ISPs , priorities, bandwidth, time of the day, solar storms and of course the flat shape of the plainet
But maybe the stress of programming while on the edge of a cliff until a task is completed would increase productivity and coding speed, that would be edge computing

One thing you missed: you can force the edge function near your database by specifying the region. You get the colocation and no cold starts, with the same or better latency as normal serverless functions.

I'd be curious to see those platforms compared with Cloudflare Workers, which can leverage the built-in globally-distributed Durable Objects datastore. Not a proper database, but viable for some use cases.
